<HEAD>Psychiatrist Held Liable For $1.9 Million For Liason</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury ordered a psychiatrist to pay nearly $ 1.9 million to a female patient with whom he had sex numerous times over a 12-year period, billing her for each visit. The <ORGANIZATION> Multnomah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury deliberated for five hours Thursday before reaching its verdict against Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petroske </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. The woman, a 55-year-old former elementary school teacher, was awarded $ 832,000 in general damages for pain and suffering, $ 1 million in punitive damages and $ 43,800 in lost wages. Testimony and evidence presented during the two-week trial indicated <PERSON> Petroske </PERSON> began treating the woman in 1967 and started having sexual relations with her in 1975. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Huegli </PERSON>, the woman's attorney, said <PERSON> Petroske </PERSON> ended the sexual relations in early 1987 while he was being investigated by the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiners </ORGANIZATION> about allegations that he was having sex with another patient. <PERSON> Petroske </PERSON> admitted he lied to the state board about the number of patients with whom he had sexual relations. In early July, the board suspended him from practice for 90 days, fined him $ 5,000 and placed him on probation for 10 years. <PERSON> Petroske </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, told jurors during closing arguments that her client is `` not going to be practicing medicine under any circumstances after this case is over.'' <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> admitted <PERSON> Petroske </PERSON> had inflicted physical damage on the patient, but she contended it was not permanent. <PERSON> Huegli </PERSON>, however, said other doctors thought the woman suffered permanent brain damage from what he called a `` long, insidious, poisoning regimen'' of drugs prescribed by <PERSON> Petroske </PERSON>. <PERSON> Huegli </PERSON> said <PERSON> Petroski </PERSON> billed the woman for all her visits, including the ones in which they engaged in sex.
