<HEAD>American Red Cross Focusing On Long-Term Aid To Soviet Armenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> has begun focusing on long-term plans to help earthquake-stricken Soviet <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> rebuild its destroyed and damaged health care facilities. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, said the pipeline of emergency aid supplies is full and flowing well, and no further immediate aid is needed at this time. Priority attention is being given to the construction of a new general hospital, he told a news conference Friday. The earthquake destroyed the only one, killing all doctors and staff inside the building. In a related development, the office of President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his son and grandson are flying to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> over the Christmas weekend to deliver toys and medical supplies to earthquake victims. <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, 35, a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> real estate developer, and his son, <PERSON> George </PERSON>, 12, will spend about six hours in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the Armenian capital, on Christmas Day. The Bushes are traveling to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> as volunteers for <ORGANIZATION> Americares </ORGANIZATION>, a private relief agency that has chartered a DC-8 cargo plane to transport supplies to the region when 55,000 people were killed in the earthquake and about 500,000 were left homeless. <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> has received $ 3.5 million in cash contributions and pledges for <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> disaster relief and that more money is coming in `` every hour.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> will use the funds to help replace health and medical facilities that were destroyed by the Dec. 7 earthquake. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> will be prepared to help fill any gaps that appear at the request of the Soviet <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, he said. <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON> said priority long-term needs in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> include: _ The building of a general hospital to replace one that was totally destroyed in the quake _ The creation of a facility to make and install artificial limbs _ The establishment of a permanent tracking center to trace families of earthquake victims _ A disaster preparedness program to reduce deaths and injuries in the event of another earthquake in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> _ The rebuilding and expansion of a destroyed school for handicapped children <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON>, who returned Thursday from an inspection tour of the disaster areas in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, said 27,000 railroad cars of relief supplies have arrived so far in addition to 148 planes carrying emergency equipment. He said Soviet officials have been conscientious in keeping track of the incoming supplies. They have promised to return expensive equipment to donors or to seek permission to use it elsewhere once it is no longer needed in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, he said. There have been reports of confusion and inept rescue efforts at the disaster scene, but <PERSON> Schuster </PERSON> said he believes the work went well given the immensity of the destruction and the relative inexperience of Soviet officials in disaster relief. `` Given the size of the disaster, I think they responded well,'' he said. `` It's impossible to have a disaster site in which there is not confusion initially.'' In addition, he said, it should be noted that in the first day or so, `` all of the people present were affected; they all lost family members.'' `` The people displayed wonderful warmth and dignity,'' <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON> said. `` Time after time they expressed their thanks to the American public, particularly to thank those in the <LOCATION> American-Armenian </LOCATION> community,'' he said. `` When they stopped to thank us on the streets the profusion of gratitude made it difficult to hold back tears _ theirs and ours.'' <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> helped deal with the crisis effectively and offered all forms of cooperation to its American counterpart. `` Bad times bring good people together,'' <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON> said. In addition to the $ 3.5 million in cash and pledges, <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> has received more than $ 8 million worth of medical and other supplies and shipped them to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. These include kidney dialysis machines, blood collection bags, plaster dressings, needles and syringes, finger splints, bandages, antiseptics, sutures, cervical collars, antibiotics, orthopedic pins, ultrasound machines, plastic eating utensils, blankets and plastic sheeting.
