<HEAD>Lobbyist John Gonella Dead At 71</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonella </PERSON>, a former aide to President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> lobbyist, died Friday at his <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> home at age 71. <PERSON> Gonella </PERSON>, most recently an assistant to the vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroads </ORGANIZATION>, began his career in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1949, when he moved here to work as an information officer for the embassy of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. He was a press spokesman and congressional liaison with a number of firms before joining the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s congressional relations office in 1965. He joined the Johnson White House staff in 1966 and served as a congressional liaison through 1969. <PERSON> Gonella </PERSON> worked as a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consultant for two years and then worked from 1971-77 on the staffs of Sens. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. During the 1950s, <PERSON> Gonella </PERSON> also wrote a golf column for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gonella </PERSON>, a native of Dollar, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Glasgow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> with degrees in economics and political science. He served in the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> during World War II and came to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION