<HEAD>Oil Spills In Pacific After Tug Hits Barge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with size of slice increases to 30 miles;
at least 50 birds found with oil on feathers; oil seen on beach,
other detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fuel oil from a leaking barge began washing ashore on resort beaches of the southwestern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> coast Friday, and at least 50 birds were found with oil on their feathers, officials said. The barge trailed an oil slick that grew to 30 miles long and 100 feet wide in the hours after a Thursday night collision with a tugboat, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Authorities closed 1 -LCB- to 2 miles of beach in the <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shores </LOCATION> area near here, on the north side of <LOCATION> Grays </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, where oiled birds were found. The area contains numerous wetlands and marshes that are home to migratory waterfowl. Rescue teams were being mobilized to try and clean and save as many birds as possible, authorities said. `` The latest reports I'm getting indicate an average of 12 dead or distressed birds are being found every quarter of a mile along the beach,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, a spokesman for the state Divison of Emergency Management. The leaking barge was towed south to the mouth of the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which separates <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. It bobbed 25 miles offshore Friday night while authorities waited for daylight to assess how best to repair it. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state officials estimated some 70,000 gallons of oil had spilled from the barge, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Steelquist </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION>. The oil was leaking from a tank holding about 250,000 gallons of oil, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Eldo </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLong </PERSON> in <LOCATION>