<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The second-degree murder conviction of a woman who claimed the `` baby blues'' caused her to run over her infant son with a car was set aside Friday by a judge who found the woman innocent by reason of insanity. <PERSON> Sheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Massip </PERSON>, 24, who testified that post-partum depression drove her to kill the colicky, constantly crying boy, was not guilty of murder, said <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>. `` I do not believe the prosecution's evidence established that she had the requisite mental state of malice aforethought,'' the judge said. He said while he knew his ruling was unusual, he felt he had no choice. Unless overturned on appeal by the prosecution, the judge's ruling invalidates a Nov. 17 jury verdict of second-degree murder, which called for a sentence of 15 years to life <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> delivered what he referred to as an `` unprecedented'' decision: first reducing the charge against her from second-degree murder to voluntary manslaughter, then ruling that she was not guilty by reason of insanity. The decision, however, still leaves the defendant eligible for commitment to a mental hospital for up to 11 years. `` This is new ground that we plowed today,'' the judge said in an interview with the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times after issuing his ruling. `` I do n't know of another court that came to a decision like the one I ded to set aside the jury verdict altogether. `` I know people will say I've overstepped my bounds. But the more I thought about it, the more I realized I did n't have any choice but to find her insane. ... She was bonkers.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON> welcomed the verdict. `` I was praying the people would understand,'' she said outside court. `` The jury did not understand, but I'm thankful that the judge did.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON> testified at the trial that on April 29, 1987, her own 23rd birthday, she hit her 6-week-old son, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, on the head with a garden tool, then put him under the wheels of the family station wagon, ran over him and put his body in a trash can. Defense witnesses said an exceptionally bad case of post-partum depression, a hormonal ailment known as the `` baby blues,'' was to blame. Defense attorney <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimes </PERSON> said the young mother was wracked by lack of sleep and hallucinations and that she heard voices telling her to put the boy out of his misery.
