<SECOND>PM-Cajun Christmas, Bjt,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heaux, Heaux Heaux: Levee Bonfires Lead Papa Noel to Cajun
Christmas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Down here, where folks wish you a `` Joyeux Noel'' instead of `` Merry Christmas,'' <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION>'s sleigh gives way to <PERSON> Papa </PERSON> <PERSON> Noel </PERSON>'s Cajun canoe and people build bonfires to light his way on Christmas Eve. `` I do n't know how that sleigh would run down here. If it needs snow he'd be in trouble. I guess that's why he comes down the river in a pirogue'' _ a flat-bottomed canoe, said <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON>, the police and fire chief of <LOCATION> Gramercy </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gramercy </PERSON> has a population of 3,600, except for Christmas Eve when upwards of 40,000 people crowd into town for the lighting of the bonfires along the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> levee, <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON> said. For 260-plus years the bonfires have blazed to guide <PERSON> Papa </PERSON> <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> down the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> to the small south <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> communities about 30 miles north of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. `` The bonfires are an old tradition passed on from my grandfather and his grandfather and all the other grandfathers, I guess,'' said the 65-year-old <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON>, who has been in charge of building the bonfires for 50 years. People began building the structures they'll torch on Christmas Eve almost a month in advance. `` They used to be just simple teepees but about eight years ago people started getting real imaginative in what they made. Now it's amazing to see what they come up with,'' <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON> said About 100 bonfires a year in the shape of riverboats, plantation homes, cabins and Viking ships spring up on the river banks along a three-mile stretch. In fact, the builders' imaginations soared to such heights that size restrictions were imposed. Bonfires can be no larger than 12-feet wide and no taller than 25 feet. `` Those are about the only restrictions,'' <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON> said. The crowds attracted by the celebration bring traffic that backs up for miles along State 44, but <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON> said he does n't consider it a problem. `` It may be a problem for the folks in the cars, but not for us. They can only go about three or four miles an hour so it's not dangerous and they can watch the bonfires just fine,'' he reasoned. Not everyone will be stacked up in traffic. At least six river boats will carry thousands of people upriver from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to watch. `` This is the second year we've done it, and we sold out before we even advertised or planned it this year. We added a third boat, the River Rose, and still have better than 200 people on a waiting list,'' said <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Viator </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paddlewheels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. For between $ 35 and $ 55, those on the various ships get dinner, champagne, jazz and about an eight-hour trip, cruise officials said <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON> and his 12-man crew worked almost three weeks to build a 38-foot-long pyre that looks like a shrimp boat. They cut willow trees, which he said burn best and make a `` beautiful fire,'' and carefully assembled them. <PERSON> Oubre </PERSON> said watching his creations go up in smoke each year is n't sad in spite of the work and time that go into them `` No, that's why you build them,'' he said. `` You've got it in mind all the time to see them burn so you look forward to that part most of all.''
</TEXT>
