<HEAD>Nicaragua-Honduras Bickering Puts Peace Talks In Jeopardy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `Honduran Foreign...' to restore dropped word
in quote. Inserts 2 grafs after 18th, `In both...' to add rebel
attack. Pickup 19th pvs, `The regional...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bickering between <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> is threatening a summit planned for next month by Central American leaders anxious to end the civil wars and hostilities in the region. The latest stumbling block comes from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hague </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> agreed this week to hear <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s claims that <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> has been harboring and supporting U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, who are fighting <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government. Honduran Foreign Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> said Wednesday the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s decision threatens the future of negotiated settlements to the region's problems. He said the court's move is politically charged and sets `` a judicial precedent totally incompatible with peace negotiations.'' In addition, President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> has threatened to boycott regional peace talks unless <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> drops its World Court case. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> and the foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> met earlier this month in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. There they agreed that heads of state would convene in January in an effort to breathe new life into the stalled August 1987 peace plan. The plan sets three-month deadlines for cease-fires in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. It also mandates that governments of all five nations enact political amnesties and democratic freedoms and reconcile with political opposition groups. It calls for an end to outside aid for rebel insurgencies and a ban on the use of one country's territory to destabilize another. The peace proposal was written by President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, who was awarded the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for his effort. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> says anti-government Nicaraguan rebels and refugees camp exist on Honduran territory because of a lack of democratic freedoms in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` For reasons of national security, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> does n't want the Contras,'' <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said. `` Nor do we desire the presence of more than 60,000 refugees from <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' However, <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> can not eject the Contras because, `` We would be accused of being responsible for massacres and violating human rights.'' <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> denounced what he called the Sandinista practice of using international organizations to pressure other nations. But <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> hailed the court's decision, and Nicaraguan President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> should accept it. The same court ruled in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s favor in 1986 in a suit against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support of the Contras. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has refused to recognize the court's jurisdiction in the area. As the main judicial organ of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, the court has no enforcement powers. The <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> plan sought to end the Honduran problem as well as long wars in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. But the heady days following the 1987 signing later turned to disappointment and frustration. The four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> _ blame <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and its largest backer, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, for the persistent turmoil. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is trying to militarize the region and find a pretext to invade <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. In both <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, talks between leftist guerrillas and the two U.S.-backed governments have fallen apart. Wars rage on with no end in sight. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> on Friday, leftist rebels attacked the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> with car bombs and explosives, killing at least three people and wounding at least 35, officials said. The assault on the military headquarters compound and on a nearby government health clinic appeared to be part of a major rebel offensive. The regional talks did lead to a cease-fire agreement in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> last March that sharply curtailed fighting there. A month earlier, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government cut off military aid to the Contras. About 10,000 Contra fighters have now moved back to base camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. The presidents last met in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> on Jan. 15, the date set by the <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> plan to mark the end of the wars and full democracy. Instead, they signed a statement vowing to continue their efforts. <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, whose government is fighting growing rebel activity, said further meetings would be useless unless concrete progress could be made.
