<HEAD>Addict Won't Be Home for Christmas _ And He's Glad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A crack addict desperate for treatment brought police his paraphernalia, then smashed windows at two precincts before a judge relented and sentenced him to a drug program he calls his `` best Christmas gift yet.'' `` I will thank him for giving me an opportunity for starting my life back over. He is an understanding man, one of very few,'' <PERSON> Alexis </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> said Friday of <ORGANIZATION> Bronx </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, 34, said his life had bordered on the insane until <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> sentenced him to 90 days in a drug treatment program. As a crack cocaine addict, <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> lost his job as a construction worker. He stopped paying bills. He became irresponsible and dirty. His wife of two years, <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> <PERSON> Coulter </PERSON>, feared for their 11-month-old son and her two daughters, now 12 and 13. Last July, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Coulter </PERSON> threw him out of their home in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s tough <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> section `` because I was doing wrong,'' he said. `` She is a Christian and I did n't want to be around her.'' `` It's bad to see a good husband turn into a monster. I've known him nine years and I had never seen that side of him,'' Miss <PERSON> Coulter </PERSON> said. `` I was praying he would get into a program before it was too late. He was getting out of hand.'' <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> knew he was getting out of hand, so he turned for help. He applied for admission at several <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> hospital programs and one in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` They all told me they were filled up. Until February or the end of January. That was too far for me to look forward to,'' <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> said. On Oct. 28, he sought help from the desk sergeant at the 47th Precinct. That did not work, so <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> tried something else: He placed a syringe and some crack vials on the sergeant's desk. `` I did n't know what else to do,'' <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> said. `` They roughed me up. They were very shocked that I did this. They did n't understand.'' And neither did the judge who handled the case, releasing him two days later without sending him to treatment. On Nov. 5, <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> tossed a chair through the window of the 48th Precinct. Another judge put him in the streets without treatment. On Nov. 14, he threw a padlock through a window of the 46th Precinct. He was processed by a third judge who did not offer treatment. `` I told them I needed help,'' <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> said. All the pending cases of drug charges and criminal mischief came together Dec. 1 before <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, who decided to do something. `` I got a call from the judge on Tuesday the 20th. From the judge himself,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sierra </PERSON>, a worker at and graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Out </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It was strange. To me, a judge has a lot to do. He went out of his way to help this particular person. The probation report was not favorable.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> said the program, which is funded by donations and other churches, has 58 beds and 600 people on the waiting list. One bed was available and <PERSON> Vega </PERSON> got it. <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, who had previously written to the program, was given a 90-day sentence Wednesday to Way Out. `` He's got a long way to go here,'' <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> said. `` It is a strain on his life. We are a very strict program.'' `` Strict'' means no leaving the program for two months, no visitors, no cursing, no smoking and plenty of prayer. The <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Attorney </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gentile </PERSON>, commended the judge and said `` this case dramatizes the critical need for treatment upon demand for all individuals addicted to drugs.'' No one knows it better than <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, who said, `` I think -LRB- the judge -RRB- gave me the best Christmas gift yet, to redeem my life back over.''
