<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Jury's Murder Verdict Against `Baby Blues' Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A murder conviction returned against a mother who admitted killing her ailing son by running him over with a car was rejected by a judge who said the woman was driven insane by post-childbirth depression. Superior Court Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>, in announcing his ruling, said he believed <PERSON> Sheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Massip </PERSON>, 24, was made insane by what some health experts call postpartum depression or `` baby blues.'' `` I know people will say I've overstepped my bounds,'' <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> told a stunned <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> courtroom as he announced the decision Friday. `` But the more I thought about it, the more I realized I did n't have a choice but to find her insane. ... She was bonkers.'' Prosecutors said they will review whether an appeal can be filed on grounds that <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>'s ruling went beyond his authority. `` We believe, on a cursory review of material, that he exceeded his authority,'' Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Borris </PERSON> said. `` We believe the best that he could have done is order a new trial.'' <PERSON> Borris </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> did n't first inform attorneys about his decision, as judges often do when they are about to issue a reversal. The judge said afterward that he had not decided what the ruling would be until the moment he delivered it. Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON>, 24, had been convicted of second-degree murder. <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> reduced the charge to voluntary manslaughter, but then ruled that she was not guilty by reason of insanity, essentially negating the voluntary manslaughter conviction. She still faces a maximum sentence of 11 years confinement in a mental hospital. Her jury conviction called for 15 years to life in prison. The judge ordered Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON> to surrender Feb. 3 for at least 90 days of psychiatric observation. He then will decide if she needs further treatment. Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON>'s family burst into cheers after the decision, which came during a hearing originally scheduled for her sentencing on the murder conviction. `` I could n't have asked God for a better Christmas present,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON>, who read a Bible before the decision. `` I got the gift of life.'' Her former husband, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Massip </PERSON>, whom she testified refused to help care for the child, fled the court in tears and refused to talk to reporters. He divorced Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON> shortly after her arrest. During her trial, Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON> admitted killing her 6-week old son, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>. But she testified that the child cried 15 to 18 hours a day, adding that she heard voices telling her to put the infant out of his misery. Experts summoned to testify by her lawyer said she had a severe case of postpartum depression, brought on by hormonal imbalance sometimes associated with childbirth. The rare disorder is believed to spur severe anxiety, delusions and even violence in approximately three of every 1,000 new mothers. On April 29, 1987, Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON>'s 23rd birthday, she tried to toss the child in front of a car near her <LOCATION> Fullerton </LOCATION> home, but the driver swerved and missed him. She then beat the infant on the head and finally placed him face-up under the tire of her <ORGANIZATION> Volvo </ORGANIZATION> station wagon and ran him over. After the killing, she first told investigators the child had been stolen by a red-haired mystery woman with a gun. But the child's body was found in a trash can. `` The pain has n't gone away. I have to live with the death of my son, the loss of my son, for the rest of my life,'' Ms. <PERSON> Massip </PERSON> said after the ruling. `` I pray that this does n't happen to anyone else.'' The judge's decision came after an impassioned plea from defense attorney <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimes </PERSON>. `` There's nothing in human experience that can justify what <PERSON> Sheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Massip </PERSON> did ... other than the fact that she was crazy at the time,'' <PERSON> Grimes </PERSON> argued.
