<HEAD>PLO, Shiite Militia Make New Peace Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Mieh Mieh is correct</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militia have reached a new peace pact to end their bloody 3-year conflict, <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> newspapers reported today. The papers published the 11-point pact, which is the sixth since 1985 when Amal moved against Palestinian refugee camps to prevent <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> from rebuilding a power base in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The five earlier accords fell apart, and there is widespread doubt the latest accord will hold. More than 3,000 people have been killed and 10,000 wounded in the Amal-PLO conflict. Amal has an estimated 10,000 armed militiamen. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> has 4,500 guerrillas based in the <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION> region, 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, which supports Amal, last month withdrew 66 truce observers from the highlands east of <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>. That raised fears of major clashes, but so far only localized skirmishes have occurred. The new pact provides for a disengagement of forces and the removal of frontline barricades to enforce a cease-fire between Amal and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> around <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, provincial capital of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The conflict has centered on the city and its environs since <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s fighters were driven out of their strongholds in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s refugee camps by rival Syrian-backed Palestinian factions in July, something <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> had failed to do Amal and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> pledged in the accord to resolve friction by peaceful means and reopen all roads in the region for unrestricted movement. The accord stipulated that Amal should lift its 3-year siege of the Rashadiyeh refugee camp in the southern port of Tyre. About 18,000 Palestinians live there. It also provided for repairing the devastation in <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ein </PERSON> el-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh camps and repatriating thousands of displaced Palestinians and Shiites in the region. The leftist Sunni Moslem Nasserite militia, which has stayed neutral in the Amal-PLO conflict, will oversee the new cease-fire.
