<HEAD>Parliament Passes Tax Reform Package</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS graf 8 beginning: After the ... to show Takeshita
took over acting finance portfolio. Picks up graf 9 beginning:
`Tatsuo Murayama ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s bid to reform the tax system today cleared its last hurdle when the upper house of parliament passed the measures after 24 hours of delaying tactics by opposition parties. The new laws give <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> a 3 percent sales tax and reduce its heavy reliance on direct taxes by cutting corporate and upper-level income taxes. The legislation is to take effect April 1. Opposition parties introduced censure motions against <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> and four other government officials Friday afternoon and then shuffled to the podium at a snail's pace to delay voting. The tactics carried parliament through its first overnight session in 13 years. Opposition parties have blocked previous attempts by other premiers to overhaul the tax system, which was drafted by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> occupation authorities in the lean years after <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s defeat in World War II. Voting on the tax bills took place more than 24 hours after the censure motions were introduced. Legislators from the <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Socialist and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Communist parties left the chamber in a show of protest, and the bills were quickly approved by the majority <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>. Since the <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> administration formally submitted the tax reform package to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in July, opposition legislators led by the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> have boycotted sessions, demanding the government first fully investigate a high-level stock-trading scandal. The scandal, involving <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> and other top officials who profited from questionable sales of unlisted stocks bought at bargain prices, has led to the resignations of politicians, business leaders and media executives, including Finance Minister <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>, who stepped down on Dec. 9. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> took over the finance portfolio then. <PERSON> Tatsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Murayama </PERSON> was one of the chief architects of the tax reform package. A former <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> bureaucrat, he is a considered a tax specialist and played a leading role in the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s tax review committee, which he has chaired since 1985. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and local business groups on Friday protested the sales tax at a rally in <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s hometown. About 100 people shouting `` Destroy the tax bill'' and calling for the resignation of the Cabinet marched near the <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> family's sake brewery in <LOCATION> Kakeai-cho </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Shimane </LOCATION> prefecture, organizer <PERSON> Jiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Wada </PERSON> said. A study by the <ORGANIZATION> Shimouma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> consumers' group, says that under the new tax plan, a typical four-member household with an annual income of $ 53,225 will pay $ 1,305 less in income and residents' taxes, but the new sales tax will cost it an additional $ 500.
