<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The southern province of <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> has held communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s first civil service examination, and 11,000 of the 120,000 applicants were selected for government employment, a report said today. The examination in September was reminiscent of the system used in imperial <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where civil servants also were selected through tests. In present-day <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, however, the functions of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government officials often overlap, and political connections frequently play a role in obtaining jobs and promotions. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> proposed a civil service system, suggesting government employees not engaged in political work should obtain jobs on the basis of an examination, and wages and promotions should depend on merit. `` The idea of giving priority to seniority and other worn-out concepts that stifle people's initiative and creativity should be eradicated,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> examination was `` a prelude to the civil service system,'' said the independent <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Pao </PERSON> newspaper, quoting the pro-government <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The examination was adminstered to 120,000 people in an `` open, fair and competitive'' manner, the report said. About 11,000 applicants passed the examination, including workers, high school and university graduates, and 3,000 people from rural areas, the report said. It did not give a breakdown of participants by age or sex. The new employees will work in provincial departments, including security, courts, finance and revenue, the report said.
