<SECOND>AM-Ryzhkov, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Where's Gorbachev? Kremlin's No. 2 Man Thrust Into Limelight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>, considered a stodgy technocrat, has suddenly been thrust into the public eye during the disaster caused by the Armenian earthquake. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s dynamic leader, President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, has retreated into an unusual silence and been absent from public view after making a brief trip to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> the morning after the Dec. 7 earthquake. Until he returned to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last week, <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> received heavy coverage in the state-run media doing the things Soviets have come to expect from the more voluble <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> directed the machinery of government in full view of TV cameras, hugged homeless Armenians and met crowds on street corners. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, by contrast, rushed home from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, spent a stormy weekend in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and has not been seen in public since Dec. 11. There were no indications that <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>'s prominence and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s absence signaled any realignment in the Kremlin or that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was ill. But it was suddenly <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> who represented the Kremlin throughout the burst of publicity given by the Soviet media to the earthquake. The careers of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> have been linked. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> was appointed to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> in April 1985, a month after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took power. He was assigned to head the Soviet government in September 1985, and is considered an important player in <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic reform plans. But the earthquake _ and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s absence _ gave the 59-year-old <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> an opportunity to shed a colorless image and gain daily television exposure. `` Thank you, thank you, thank you,'' Armenians called to <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> in the earthquake-damaged city of <LOCATION> Kirovakan </LOCATION>. `` People are very satisfied,'' said an elderly woman, pressing <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>'s hands. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> responded to people with smiles and promises of help. `` He's gotten a high profile, but whether it works to his advantage, I do n't know,'' said one diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. That will depend on how <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>'s work in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> is perceived by other <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leaders, he said. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> acknowledged widespread reports of disorganization in the relief efforts during a news conference in the Armenian capital <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> on Dec. 12. But he said after a bad start the organization had begun to improve. In the spirit of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or greater openness, <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> directly answered all the questions put to him by foreign and Soviet reporters in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>. He showed little emotion in his answers. But when reporters asked him about ethnic troubles between Armenians and Azerbaijanis over control of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region, he began jabbing the air with his hand and said, `` We do n't understand these people. While the whole country is helping them, they are raising these questions. We think the Armenian people must reject them.'' It was the same issue that caused <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to show his anger on Soviet television. Asked about allegations by Armenian activists that Soviet officials planned to move orphaned Armenians out of the earthquake area and repopulate it with Russians, he responded, `` What kind of morals do those people have?'' `` They do n't need <LOCATION> Karabakh </LOCATION>. They are waging a battle for power, and they must be stopped,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. Many Armenians are upset with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for refusing to give in to their demands to annex Nagorno-Karabakh from <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s absence from public view was `` normal for the week after the quake, but this week it's a little more difficult to explain,'' said the foreign diplomat. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has not missed any events that could be considered important enough to demand his presence, and the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> has continued issuing documents over <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s name. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> sent a message of condolence to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> after the crash of a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jet in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> on Wednesday.
