 <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, first and perhaps the only woman named to the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cabinet, has the resume of a topnotch <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> lawyer and the charm of a quintessential Southern belle. Her ability to disarm even the toughest critics has earned her widespread popularity on <LOCATION> Capital </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, even among many Democrats. And her reputation as an able government official appears to have weathered harsh evaluations of her <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration tenure as transportation secretary. `` She is a woman of great ability with many friends in both parties on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that must confirm her Saturday she was named as labor secretary by President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The choice left just one Cabinet spot open, that of energy secretary. Relentlessly cheerful, Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> is at age 52 half of what inside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> likes to call a `` power couple.'' Her husband is <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, who unsuccessfully sought his party's presidential nomination They have a Watergate apartment and a miniature schnauzer named `` Leader.'' Known as `` <PERSON> Liddy </PERSON>,'' a nickname she picked herself, Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Salisbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, the only daughter of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanford </PERSON>, a small-town florist, and <