rs before her term expired to help him run for president. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> is generally credited with softening her husband's hatchet-man image, although she dismisses that, seeming to suggest he was always really a softy: `` He's sort of the way I always knew him. With no prior background in the transportation field, Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was named in 1983 as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s transportation secretary. She pushed for mandatory seat belt laws, tighter screening procedures in airports and more sophisticated anti-collision devices for airliners. But she was criticized in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for spending more time on press releases than real improvements. Critics contended she more often than not unveiled new regulatory procedures after the department had been pushed into it by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or the courts. Critics also faulted her for approving a string of airline mergers that concentrated much of the airline industry into a half-dozen large carriers. In 1987, a trade journal called her DOT stewardship `` little more than a planned media event.'' And The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monthly headlined a cover story: `` Charming Her Way to the White House; air travel stinks, auto safety's a joke and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> still loves <PERSON> Liddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> stepped down a year ago to help her husband's presidential campaign, saying the move had nothing to do with the criticism and declaring she was glad to join him on the campaign trail after years of living `` like passing ships in the night. Sen. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> noted her new appointment with a combination of pride and humor. `` It looks like TV dinners for me again, but I'll still probably vote for her confirmation,'' he said.
