<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The women at the birthday party enjoyed watching a male stripper shuck his fake sheriff's deputy outfit, but police gave him a different reception on his way home. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bateham </PERSON>, 27, was charged with impersonating a police officer. The charges were later dropped, but <PERSON> Bateham </PERSON> suffered a separated shoulder in a motorcycle accident prior to his arrest. The stripper started off his act Oct. 16 wearing a fake sheriff's deputy uniform with `` <LOCATION> Sarasota </LOCATION> Sheriff's Office'' patches on the arms, a mail-order `` County Mounty'' badge and a gun belt After performing at the birthday party, <PERSON> Bateham </PERSON> said he put a jacket over his uniform and was driving toward his girlfriend's house when a police car started following him He had an accident on a dead end road. `` When -LRB- the officers -RRB- walked up to me, I told them I was a dancer and it was a BB gun. One reached over and threw the gun on the ground, and the rest is history.'' When he arrived in court Thursday to stand trial, he learned the misdemeanor charge was being dropped. Defense attorney <PERSON> Ty </PERSON> <PERSON> Trayner </PERSON> said a person can not be convicted of impersonating a police officer just because he is dressed for the part. He has to try something official, like threaten to arrest somebody. So <LOCATION> Bateham </LOCATION> is free to continue using the uniform with Male Express. `` The deputy uniform is our most popular outfit,'' he said. `` I'll just take more precautions from now on. I wo n't wear the shirt or gun belt when I'm traveling.''
