<HEAD>Russian `Grandfather Frost' For Hire At Christmas, New Year's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet holiday customs look a lot like American ones, but in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the jolly man with the fluffy white beard and red suit rides in a taxi and few of the presents he brings run on batteries. Instead of standing in line at a shopping mall to sit on <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION>'s lap, many Soviet children get house calls from <ORGANIZATION> Ded </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moroz </ORGANIZATION> _ Grandfather Frost _ and <PERSON> Snegurochka </PERSON>, a beautiful snow maiden dressed in white Five-year-old <PERSON> Olga </PERSON>'s eyes lit up as Ded <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Snegurochka </PERSON> walked into her family's apartment Saturday morning. The couple sang, danced and told riddles with the little girl. Ded <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON> then opened his sack and pulled out a huge teddy bear, which <PERSON> Olga </PERSON>'s father had handed him secretly beforehand. `` It's so beautiful,'' said <PERSON> Olga </PERSON>, who was dressed in a powder-blue princess costume and wore a shiny tiara and a big light blue bow atop her head. Ded <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Snegurochka </PERSON> wished the family happy New Year and trudged through the mounds of snow back to their hired yellow taxi. They had about 30 more stops before the day was through. `` I do n't feel like it's New Year's unless I dress up like this and visit little children,'' said <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Krylov </PERSON>, 37, who has been playing Ded Moroz for nine years. `` Our -LRB- Soviet -RRB- children believe so much that <PERSON> Ded </PERSON> <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Snegurochka </PERSON> are real,'' said <PERSON> Lyuda </PERSON> <PERSON> Golubgikova </PERSON>, 33, a six-year veteran <LOCATION> Snegurochka </LOCATION>. `` I love to see their eyes shine when we walk in.'' After the Bolshevik revolution in 1917, the primary winter holiday in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> switched from Christmas, celebrated Jan. 7 in the Russian Orthodox faith, to New Year's. <PERSON> Olga </PERSON>'s parents were among about 4,000 people who each paid a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> business called <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> about $ 9 to have the holiday couple bring New Year's greetings to their children between Dec. 24 and Jan. 5, said <PERSON> Tamara </PERSON> <PERSON> Korovina </PERSON>, who hired the cast of characters. People signed up for Ded <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON> house calls at Detsky Mir, the largest children's store in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, located in the center of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Soviets flock to <PERSON> Detsky </PERSON> Mir from across the nation and buy about 500,000 toys per day during the holiday season, said <PERSON> Garnik </PERSON> <PERSON> Oganesyan </PERSON>, director of commerce at the five-story store. <PERSON> Valentina </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, 31, went to <PERSON> Detsky </PERSON> Mir to pick up a toy for her 3-year-old son, but while shopping decided to order a visit from Ded <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON>. `` Andrusha will be so surprised! He has only seen Ded Moroz on greeting cards,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said she had no trouble finding the toy submarine her son had requested. All she had to do was fight the crowd at Detsky Mir _ which makes Christmas Eve at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> department store look calm in comparison _ and wait in line for 30 minutes. Parents whose children asked for electronic or battery-operated toys were likely to be disappointed. <PERSON> Detsky </PERSON> Mir only had a few such toys, and as soon as they went on display they were snapped up, admitted <PERSON> Oganesyan </PERSON>. `` My 11-year-old son wants an electronic game, but I do n't think I'll be able to find it,'' said a Detsky Mir employee, who asked that her name not be used. She said Soviet children usually receive just one toy, `` because for each gift a parent must run, run, run to find it and then wait, wait, wait to buy it.''
