<HEAD>Stories Behind The Names of Those Aboard Pan Am Flight 103</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The world knows them as victims, but family members and friends knew the 258 people who boarded <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> as sons and daughters, husbands and wives, students, teachers, doctors and businessmen. Here are brief sketches of the people they remember:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 At the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, flags were ordered flown at half-staff in memory of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>, an attorney with the agency's Office of Special Investigations. <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>, a 36-year-old father of two, had been in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> negotiating a treaty to allow some former <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to be deported there.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hadley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, had been studying in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and had planned to go on a different flight, but at the last minute decided to fly with a friend to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, his family said. <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> called home and left a message that he would be on the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight, said his mother, <PERSON> Sallie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON>. She said <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> was a champion fencer and a poet who wrote long letters home regularly. `` He would call me up and say, ` How're you doing, Mom? I was thinking about you today.' He did that just last week and said he was looking forward to coming home,'' she said.
