TION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, and for peace talks involving the two Koreas and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said the agency dispatch, monitored in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The Soviet side also reaffirmed its opposition to recognizing both Koreas as a means of reducing tension. It pledged it would not establish diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> despite its participation in the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympic Games and its increasing trade ties with the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> have called on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s allies, to recognize <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in exchange for their establishing relations with the North. But <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has said such moves will lead to the permanent division of the peninsula.
