<HEAD>There's More To Being A Santa Than The `Ho, Ho, Ho!'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON> is a shopping mall <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>, but he never says `` Ho, ho, ho,'' he never flirts, and he knows what to do if a frightened child wets on him. <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON> is a graduate of the `` <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claus </ORGANIZATION>,'' a nationwide how-to course sponsored by Los Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temporary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> to train a select few on the finer points of playing the jolly old elf. `` I never pictured myself as a <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>,'' says <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON>, who calls himself a cowboy _ a horseshoer by trade. `` It was really overwhelming at first.'' This is <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON>'s first experience as <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION>. His towering 6-foot-4, nearly 300-pound frame helps him play the part. But he's more than just another pretty <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Smoot </PERSON>, 42, finished his training several weeks ago after being recruited by Western to serve as one of the company's Santas. `` We approached him. He's got that look about him, that sparkle in his eye,'' said <PERSON> Darla </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, manager of Western's <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> office. Western's course is based on the concept that there's more to being Santa than wearing a red suit and laughing a loud `` Ho, ho, ho.'' `` You can put the facade on, but it does n't work,'' said <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Zink </PERSON>, national director of marketing for Western in the company's <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> office Western trained more than 3,300 Santas this year to appear at shopping malls and department stores, even restaurants and bank lobbies, across the country. There's really no university, but graduates of the course do receive a diploma from Western's `` <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claus </ORGANIZATION>.'' The company has more than 325 offices that specialize in finding temporary employees for clerical, technical, legal and accounting services. It takes its <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> business seriously. `` This is a very important job,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Zink </PERSON>, who heads Western's <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> division. `` We probably would n't spend half a day training a laborer to pick up a piano.'' Santas trained by Western must pass the company's course, which teaches them `` how to be authentic Santas,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> said. There's a 40-minute introduction video, instructions on what to say to children, suggested dialogue, lessons on how to dress like <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION>, and a requirement that each <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> know the names of all the reindeers. The course ends with a written test that prospective Santas must pass to graduate. `` Only one in 23 applicants is selected for <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> said. `` We interview a lot of people, check references and verify they are people of high character and morals.'' Western, which has provided Santas nationwide for 21 years, advises its Santas to follow the guidelines it provides when dealing with children. `` We frown upon any type of originality because it has been proven that this brings disaster,'' reads the company's manual for the `` Santa technique. Santas should address children as `` young fellow'' or `` young lady;'' refer to parents as `` folks'' because many children are adopted; never flirt _ <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> is married; ask children what toys they want for Christmas so they wo n't ask for intangible items, such as the reuniting of divorced parents; never make quick, jerky movements with small children who might be frightened by something unexpected; and if a child wets, calmly lift the child and cheerfully hand them back to the parent. Perhaps the most interesting instruction involves what most people identify with <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION>. `` We omit the `` Ho, ho, ho'' because it may frighten the children,'' the Western training manual states. `` Talk softly.''
