<BYLINE>Home For Christmas: Do Homeless Prefer The Grate?
^By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> basks in the warmth of a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Christmas, the homeless people he said prefer to live on the streets gather around their flameless urban campfires in the wet chill of the capital. A sparsely decorated pine tree stands propped against a street lamp as a group of sturdy young men stamp their feet on a street grate above the city's underground network of heat and steam pipes. These men are four blocks from the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, where this week <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> spoke of the homeless during a television interview with <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>. `` Those people still prefer -LRB- being -RRB- out there on the grates or the lawn to going into one of those shelters,'' the president said in the interview broadcast Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> called <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remarks `` mean spirited and insensitive,'' saying the number of homeless has increased dramatically during his administration. Estimates range in the hundreds of thousands, with more than 15,000 in the nation's capital But some of the `` grate people'' say <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was correct, in a sense, about their preferences. `` Given the choice of one of the grates and the urine and the lice and the maggots -LRB- in shelters -RRB-, I'll take the grates,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, as a stiff, hot updraft warmed a small circle of men in their 20s and 30s. Others said the shelters were full anyway; they'd been turned away. None of them much liked what <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said about street people, especially his suggestion that most are mentally retarded. The president spoke of the release of mental patients from hospitals in the face of civil liberties demands: `` They wanted freedom, but they walked out to where there was nothing for them, and they are a large percentage of that group that you see out there,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. Again, some of the street people think <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was partially correct. `` It was all done with good intentions when they started releasing people who were not a danger to others,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Moens </PERSON>, 29, who is clean, well-dressed, articulate and living over the grates across the street from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` But it's more inhuman to let them stay out here and fend for themselves Some of them are psychotic and should be locked up.'' <ORGANIZATION> Moens </ORGANIZATION> said the young men in his group are on the streets to avoid the drug addicts, serious drunks, transvestites, criminals and psychotics who they say infest some of the shelters in the city. The Sheriff, Go Go <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> and the others who live over the grates make an odd family. A few said they have jobs but ca n't save enough to pay the minimum $ 65 a week for flophouse rent. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON> there are lots of jobs in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>: `` How could they be out there when every week ... you'll find from 60 to 75 full pages of help-wanted ads in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> paper?'' the president asked. Go Go <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>, who prides himself on good personal hygiene and professes a deep Christian faith, said he has had several $ 3.35-an-hour, minimum-wage jobs. `` I challenge President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to live on that,'' he said. The Sheriff, who would not give his real name, showed his photo on a plastic <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> identification card and said he was working at the Pentagon and comes home to his park benches at night. He showed a recent color photo of his 11-year-old daughter. He said he sends her money every time he gets paid. `` I do n't want pity,'' he said. `` I'm just in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> trying to get a foothold. This is our living room and that's our television set.'' He pointed at a partially demolished building, a classy apartment house, a drug store and Riverside Liquors. Liquor store co-owner <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> has a different view of the grates. Some of the men are his friends. One once brought him to tears, a fellow named <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> who came in so cold he could n't fasten his jacket. `` When he asked me to help him zip up, I got an image of my 7-year-old kid, and I cried,'' said <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>. He agreed that some have serious mental problems. When one of the grate people lay down in the middle of E Street and started shooting at the sky with his fingers, <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said he telephoned for the police and an ambulance. Then, because it was lunchtime, he ordered a pizza. The pizza arrived first, and the authorities a couple of hours later, he said. And when an elderly, white-bearded derelict called Wolfman died a few weeks ago after living on the streets for more than two decades, he lay on a grate for three hours before anyone came to take away the body, <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. `` The president has a very valid point about them preferring to live on the grates rather than in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> shelters,'' said <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>. `` But criminals in prison are treated better than these people.'' Another view of the homeless was offered Saturday by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly radio `` The reality is,'' <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said, `` most of them are not much different from you or me. They are the elderly, the veterans, the physically disabled and the chronically ill. They are the drug and alcohol dependent. They're the migrant farm workers ... But in ever increasing numbers, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s homeless are working families with kids.'' <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said that while `` <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> never understood this issue'' of homelessness, Democrats were convinced his successor, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, `` will make a serious effort to deal with the tragedy of homelessness.''
