<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although chances for snow were slim in the <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> area, at least one local youngster will have a white Christmas. <PERSON> Cara </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON>, 10, earned the honor when she won the city <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION>'s first Wishing for a Winter Wonderland essay contest. A dump truck pulled up in front of her family's home Friday morning, and delivered ice shavings that had been collected at the city's two ice rinks. <PERSON> Cara </PERSON> and her friends raced through the man-made snow, slipping and sliding and making snowballs _ one of which landed squarely on the nose of Mayor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudnut </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cara </PERSON>'s winning essay selected from 1,044 entries talked about the magical qualities of snow. `` You can pretend that you are trudging through the arctic with penguins sliding into the sparkling water when you play in the snow. Or you can travel to an enchanted land or become an Olympic figure skater swishing around on the glittering ice.''
