<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's no Santa Claus in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. There is a Christmas Creek, <LOCATION> Christmas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Christmas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, Christmas Valley, <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Creek </PERSON> and Mistletoe. But <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION> is in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. There are at least 88 places nationwide with Christmas in the name, according to the Geographic Names Information System developed by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on Geographic Names. There also are several Santa Clauses, a smattering of Noels and an occasional <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> or <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> or Star or Holiday among the 2 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> place names.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HAMMOND, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A father is keeping alive the memory of his dead son with acts of Christmas kindness for residents of a school for the retarded. <PERSON> C.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, 58, collects and recycles about 10 tons of aluminum cans a year so he can treat residents of the <ORGANIZATION> Hammond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> to dinner and presents. <PERSON> C.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, or <PERSON> Jay </PERSON>, was 16 when he died eight years ago. He was retarded, but never stayed at the <ORGANIZATION> Hammond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON>, held their first party at the school about 10 years ago, using money he earned by walking the highways picking up aluminum cans and stashing bags of them in the woods until he could bring his pickup truck around. He owned his own scrap metal company. Now, diabetes keeps him from walking much, and he relies on other people to donate cans at collection bins at grocery stores, camp grounds and in his front yard in <LOCATION> Hammond </LOCATION>, 35 miles northwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. Some 40 residents of the school receive a box of candy, a dollar bill and other gifts adding up to $ 35. `` You might say, ` Well, that ai n't many,' but when you've got to wrap 320 gifts, it is,'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said.
