<HEAD>46 Die, 67 Injured When Train Crashes Into Bus in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An express passenger train slammed into a bus filled with peasants in northeast <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, killing at least 46 people, official reports said early Sunday. The train, bound for <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, was approaching a crossing in <LOCATION> Liaoning </LOCATION> province on Friday night when the bus began to cross the tracks, the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. Two rail cars overturned in the crash, it said. National television said Saturday that 84 peasants were on the bus, heading home to Inner <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>. The television report said 67 people were injured, many critically, but the later <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> report put the number at 54. The discrepancy could not immediately be resolved. The train began in the city of <LOCATION> Dandong </LOCATION> on the Chinese border with <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said the crash took place in central <LOCATION> Liaoning </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Qinghemen </LOCATION>, about 100 miles west of the provincial capital of <LOCATION> Shenyang </LOCATION>. It said the engine and a second car were overturned and three other train cars derailed. The TV showed the bus, mangled beyond recognition, and a row of bodies at the scene. Neither it nor <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said whether anyone on the train was killed. Police are investigating the cause of the accident, the TV said. The collision was the fifth major train accident this year. The most serious was a derailment in southwest <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Yunnan </LOCATION> province in January in which 88 people died. A train collision in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> in March killed 28 people, including 27 members of a Japanese high school tour group. The minister of railways, <PERSON> Ding </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangen </PERSON>, resigned in disgrace in early March after the first three accidents and his successor, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Senmao </PERSON>, promised to correct safety and maintenance failures blamed for the earlier accidents. Trains are the main means of long-distance transport in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, carrying about 1.2 billion passengers a year.
