<HEAD>Prague District Bans Further Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities in a district where independent groups this month held their first legal rally in almost 20 years have called the rally anti-socialist and banned such gatherings in the future, a newspaper said Saturday. The Communist party daily Rude Pravo said the ban was decided at a meeting Thursday of officials from <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s third district, close to the city center, and organizers of the Dec. 10 rally marking 40 years of the <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Declaration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. In the peaceful hour-long rally, called by five unofficial groups, well-known independent activists addressed a public crowd for the first time since the end of 1968's `` Prague Spring'' reforms. Several speeches called for peaceful changes in the current system. At the end, a crowd of about 3,000 approved a declaration calling for the release of all political prisoners, full religious freedom, legalization of groups independent of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> and a new constitution. Rude Pravo said the organizers of the Dec. 10 meeting `` were told openly they did not adhere to the conditions under which they got permission for the public gathering.'' `` The content of slogans and some of the performances stepped outside the boundaries of this covenant,'' wrote Rude Pravo commentator <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Boudova </PERSON>. The rally `` was aimed against <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> order and proved the real intention of organizers to misuse the gathering for political provocation,'' she said. The decision was preceded by publication in Rude Pravo Dec. 15 and 16 of readers' letters attacking the Dec. 10 meeting. `` We can not and must not let Czech Walesas infringe upon the legal order, and what is worse, trifle with serious questions of democracy and justice,'' wrote one reader Dec. 16, referring to Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Petr </PERSON> <PERSON> Uhl </PERSON>, one of the activists involved in negotiations with the authorities before the Dec. 10 gathering, said there had been no mention then of limits on the content of slogans or speeches at the rally. `` It is false, quite false, that we the independent groups have violated such conditions,'' he said. <PERSON> Uhl </PERSON> said neither of the two activists who met with authorities on Thursday were in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> over the Christmas weekend.
