<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They sliced prices to trim hair at the <ORGANIZATION> Drake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barbershop </ORGANIZATION>, a place some say is a real cut above. With a barbershop quartet harmonizing `` Easy Street'' and champagne chilling nearby, <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Merchant </PERSON> was cutting the customer's hair for the 1920s prices of 35 cents on Christmas Eve `` It's our way to commemorate the anniversary of the Drake Hotel and the barbershop,'' Merchant said. His small but classy barbershop, with its mirrors trimmed with gold paint and his barbers in white jackets and ties, is located in the arcade under the venerable, upper-crust hotel on this city's Magnificant Mile Merchant's shop charged the rates when the barbershop and hotel opened in 1920 _ 35 cents for a haircut, 25 cents for a manicure and 10 cents for a shoeshine. `` It's back to the days when a gentleman could get a haircut, a shave, manicure _ the works for under a buck,'' said Merchant. `` I found out the original prices from a 102-year-old man whose hair I cut. He used to come here in the 1920s.'' That's quite a contrast to today's <PERSON> Drake </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbershop </PERSON>, where a haircut costs $ 16 and a manicure goes for $ 12.
