<HEAD>Volcano In Northern Japan Erupts Saturday Night</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A newly active volcano in northern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> erupted again Saturday night and early Sunday, forcing about 250 residents and tourists to evacuate from nearby ski areas and hot spring resorts, police said. Police officials said no casualties or damage were reported in the eruption of 6,900-foot <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tokachi </LOCATION>, about 560 miles north of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. The volcano first erupted Monday for the first time in 26 years, sending columns of smoke rising more than a mile high and pouring mud down its slopes. Local town officials said the volcano remained relatively calm until its eruptions Saturday. The mud flow caused by the latest eruptions was reported subsiding Sunday morning, police said. However, the <LOCATION> Asahikawa </LOCATION> Weather Observation Station warned local residents Sunday that the volcano could erupt again. In 1926, heat from <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tokachi </LOCATION>'s eruption melted almost all snow on the mountain, causing mudslides that killed 144 people and injured another 200 in two nearby villages. A smaller eruption in 1962 killed four people.
