<HEAD>Christmas Surges Anew in Far-flung Places; Disaster Victims
Comforted</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos JRL2, JRL5, BEI2, BJ1, MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF DONN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The spirit of Christmas made a comeback in Peking and <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, while Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II and Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> invoked the holiday to denounce the evil of modern times and comfort those afflicted by recent catastrophes. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> telephoned Christmas greetings to members of the armed forces in distant places Saturday, talking to several selected servicemen from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, increasing numbers of foreign tourists and more exposure to foreign books and television has helped foster what one <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> newspaper called `` Christmas fever.'' Hotels for foreigners mounted Christmas displays and people bought up Christmas cards imported from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. In their latest fad, Chinese university students raised on atheism went church-hopping Christmas Eve, and thousands of them jammed <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s main Protestant and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> churches Saturday night In the black township of <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, people prepared to enjoy a day clouded in recent years by black activists' calls for `` Black Christmas'' boycotts to protest the white minority government. This year no boycotts were announced and people bought toys, sent Christmas cards, and filled holiday shopping bags without fear of reprisals for breaking a boycott. In <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basilica </LOCATION>, the pope heralded the birth of Christ and lamented the `` evil which still persists in human history and even, in a sense, is becoming deeper and more widespread.'' In parts of the world riven by recent disasters, the holiday supplied only a bare glimmer of hope. In <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 crashed Wednesday and killed all 258 board as well as others on the ground, shops remained open and churches held Christmas Eve services. Yet hearts grieved as searchers combed the countryside for more bodies. The Rev. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Keegans </PERSON>, whose home was destroyed in the crash, put Christmas preparations aside Saturday to meet with relatives of victims at a counseling center in the Roman Catholic parish hall. In <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, where a Dec. 7 earthquake killed an estimated 55,000 people, a teacher said even the holiday season could do little to provide solace. `` For us Armenians, there can be no holidays this year. No New Year's, no Christmas,'' said <PERSON> Edik </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparyan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> teacher. `` There has been too much loss, too much death.'' In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> broadcast an unprecedented second Christmas message Saturday to comfort those who suffered in the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jet disaster, the Armenian earthquake and a recent rail crash in south <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that killed 34 people. She said she wanted to offer her heartfelt sympathy and prayers to those who were injured and lost loved ones in the three disasters which `` shocked and distressed'' the entire world. Elsewhere, Christmas competed with social strife. In the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> is said to have been born, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers seemed to outnumber celebrants Saturday. A driving rain, a Palestinian general strike and heavy <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> security kept crowds slim. In <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, friends and relatives of American hostages <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON> and British captive <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> hoped the season would soften the hearts of the kidnappers. They appealed for the release of the hostages in Christmas letters published Saturday in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> newspapers. Despite social turmoil, terror, and disasters both manmade and natural, millions of children around the world felt the magic of Christmas with an innocence many of their elders lost long, long ago. In a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> apartment on Saturday, the eyes of a 5-year-old girl named <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> lit up when a couple dressed as Ded <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Snegurochka </PERSON>, <PERSON> Grandfather </PERSON> <PERSON> Frost </PERSON> and a snow maiden, walked in. Ded <PERSON> Moroz </PERSON> opened his sack and pulled out a huge teddy bear. `` It's so beautiful,'' said <PERSON> Olga </PERSON>, who was herself dressed as a princess. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in his pretaped radio speech, extended special Christmas remembrances to homeless children in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and to victims of the earthquake in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. `` Here in our country, there are children _ without homes, suffering from dire diseases _ whose Christmases will be makeshift at best,'' said the president, who is spending the holidays in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> with wife <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>. He praised the efforts of Toys for Tots and other organizations to provide gifts and other assistance for such children. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, last-minute shoppers thronged shopping malls and last-minute travelers had most airplanes booked solid. At the <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mall </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Toms </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> DelBene </PERSON> said the mall's 105 stores were packed with shoppers buying `` just one more thing.'' People were already waiting to get in when the mall opened at 8 a.m., and by noon, the parking lot was full and cars were parked on the grass, <PERSON> DelBene </PERSON> said. `` It gets more hectic every year, as merchants try to beat the prior year's figures. The trend seems to be to wait till the end,'' <PERSON> DelBene </PERSON> said.
