<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Midnight Mass; Broadcast To Soviet Union For First
Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with color from homily at
midnight Mass, CORRECT that state-run TV, sted Vatican, reported
message broadcast to Soviet Union for first time, ADDS background on
Soviet overtures to Roman Catholicism, PICKS UP 7th pvs ```It
may...'''
^By TERRY LEONARD</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> heralded the birth of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> in a midnight Mass homily for Roman Catholics worldwide Saturday, and state-run Italian television said the message was being broadcast to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for the first time. The pope, dressed in gold and white robes and carrying a crucifix, walked into <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s Basilica moments before midnight at the end of a long cortege of priests. At the same time, church bells chimed all over <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> to hail the arrival of Christmas. The pope opened the homily in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s Basilica by quoting from <PERSON> Luke </PERSON> 2:10 -11, `` I bring you good news of great joy for to you is born a savior. A text of the homily was issued in advance by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. `` We hear this voice which emanates from the depths of the night of <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>. The shepherds ` keeping watch over their flock by night' were the first to hear it. For this reason, the midnight liturgy is sometimes called ` the Shepherds' Mass,'' he said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, speaking from the papal altar under the colossal bronze canopy designed by <PERSON> Bernini </PERSON>, noted that people of different languages were listening to the same message on radio and television broadcasts of the Mass to 50 countries. The pope, seated on a white and gold throne in front of the altar, spoke to a congregation that included cardinals in red vestments, formally dressed diplomats accredited to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, and thousands of pilgrims. An announcer on the state-run <ORGANIZATION> RAI </ORGANIZATION> television network, which was feeding the Mass to other stations and networks around the world, said the message was being broadcast to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for the first time. He did not elaborate. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has shown signs of overtures to the Roman Catholic church and its domestic faithful in recent months. Earlier this year, officials allowed celebrations to mark the 1,000 anniversary of <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christendom </LOCATION> and received a delegation from the Vatican. Last year the Soviets stopped jamming the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, a radio station operated by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. On Nov. 29, they stopped interfering with signals of U.S.-funded Radio Liberty. In his midnight Mass, the pope cautioned the faithful not to be complacent, and to find the true meaning of Christmas in the words `` a savior is born to you.'' `` It may seem that people have achieved a great deal, and continue to do so, in ` saving' themselves with their own resources, so that they be self-sufficient. But they are becoming more and more convinced that they are not self-sufficient, that all the things that are termed ` civilization, progress and development' do not reach the roots of the evil which still persists in human history and even, in a sense, is becoming deeper and more widespread,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said. `` Meanwhile the words ` a savior is born to you' continue to touch what is permanent and real in man, what is profoundly true,'' the pontiff said. On Sunday, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was to lead a 10:30 a.m. Christmas Day Mass in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s, the largest church in <LOCATION> Christendom </LOCATION>. That Mass is followed by the pope's traditional Christmas Day message `` Urbi et Orbi,'' to the city and to the world. Earlier Saturday, in what has become a Christmas Eve custom, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> met with fellow Poles for the breaking of the oplatek, paper-thin unleavened bread similar to wafers used for Communion. Polish families usually begin Christmas Eve dinner by passing the wafer around the table. During the meeting with his countrymen, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, speaking in Polish, severely criticized what he called `` the evil traditions of the last decades'' in Polish politics.
