<HEAD>With Week Left To Go In 1988, NYC's Yearlong Homicide Record Broken</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least seven Christmas Eve slayings pushed the 1988 homicide total to a record with a week left in the year still to go, officials said Saturday. The seven slayings reported by early evening Saturday raised the citywide total for 1988 to 1,842, breaking the record 1981 total of 1,841, said police spokesman Sgt. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>. On an average day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, five people are murdered. City officials, both police and elected, have repeatedly blamed drugs and particularly crack for the rise in violence. In all of 1945, the <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported 291 homicides; in August 1988 alone, there were 201. Since the crack explosion in 1985, homicides have steadily increased: 1,385 in 1985, 1,582 in 1986, and 1,672 last year. As of last month, Assistant Police Chief <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said about 42 percent of this year's slayings were drug-related. `` These tragic statistics reflect the mayor's concern expressed over the past 4 -LCB- years that the federal government ought to do something about drugs flooding across our border,'' said mayoral spokesman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. The Christmas Eve slayings included a 40-year-old man stabbed to death in his East Village apartment; an unidentified man shot once over the eye in drug-plagued <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>; a 21-year-old man fatally shot after a dispute in a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> nightclub; and a 36-year-old woman found stabbed to death in her <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> apartment. On Friday, shoppers at a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> department store were sent diving for cover during a shootout between teen-agers that left one dead and three wounded. The gunfight was ignited when one teen-ager bumped another inside the store. The problem is not limited to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, there has already been a record set for the most homicides ever in a year. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ranks 10th in killings per 100,000 people, said <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. The top three are <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, he said.
