<HEAD>24 Killed In Mexico Prison Riot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with death toll at 24, breakdown of
dead, arrests of three guards and four prisoners, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TEPIC, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police stormed a prison and crushed an uprising by inmates who were denied Christmas pardons, but the warden and 23 other people were killed and six were injured in the two-day siege, officials said Saturday. `` There was a fierce gunfight lasting about 15 minutes before the special forces could quell the mutiny'' on Friday night, said police officer <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Anzaldo </PERSON>, who was on duty when the commandos attacked the prison. `` It was quite violent,'' he said in a telephone interview. Authorities have arrested four inmates and three prison guards suspected of complicity in the uprising, a state government spokesman said Saturday. One of the arrested guards, hospitalized with minor wounds, was earlier considered one of 20 hostages rescued Friday night when police stormed the prison's administrative offices and crushed the uprising, said <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> Nayarit </LOCATION> state government. The other two guards were not there during the uprising, but they may have allowed inmates and two outsiders into the office area Thursday morning, the state official said. <PERSON> Anzaldo </PERSON> said 130 commandos flown in from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> stormed the prison after a group of inmates had held 14 prison employees and visiting relatives hostage for 32 hours. An earlier attempt to storm the prison Friday was repulsed. The uprising began Thursday after the mutinous prisoners were denied pardons given at Christmas to inmates with good behavior. <PERSON> Flores </PERSON> said a preliminary report showed the mutiny began when about six inmates arrived at the warden's office Thursday to protest denial of the pardons. Two well-dressed visitors posing as lawyers approached the building at the same time and took out guns. <PERSON> Flores </PERSON> said they had entered the prison without being searched. The hostages were held in administrative offices, and the rest of the 1,200 inmates remained under control throughout the uprising on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Tepic </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Nayarit </LOCATION> state capital, 500 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The death toll from the original confrontation Thursday morning and the raids Friday night was 24: <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarado </PERSON>, the 31-year-old warden of <PERSON> Venustiano </PERSON> <PERSON> Carranza </PERSON> penitentiary; <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, head of the Fox commando unit; 19 prisoners and three unidentified people presumed to be prisoners, <PERSON> Flores </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Alvarado </PERSON> was killed in a shootout when the inmates tried to seize the warden's office Thursday, officials said. He was reported to have bled to death from a leg wound. Authorities were still trying to determine exactly how many inmates were ultimately involved in the uprising and how the firearms were brought into the prison. <PERSON> Celso </PERSON> <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Delgado </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, governor of the state of <LOCATION> Nayarit </LOCATION>, told reporters Saturday that the immediate deployment of 200 state police had kept hundreds of visiting relatives and officials from being trapped by the uprising, but some relatives were among the hostages. <PERSON> Anzaldo </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> volunteers recovered the bodies after the assault and were not immediately sure about their identities. A prisoner provided initial identifications. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> was shot shortly before nightfall Friday, when he went into the prison compound and tried to talk the inmates into surrendering. `` The answer was a hail of bullets which killed him instantly,'' a state official said. About two hours later, police lobbed dozens of tear gas canisters into the penitentiary and rushed it with automatic weapons blazing. An undetermined number of people died in the raid, which was unsuccessful. About 11 p.m. Friday the commandos staged a second raid, which killed more people and succeeded, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. At least two people besides the prison warden and commando leader were killed before special forces stormed the inmates, he said. <PERSON> Anzaldo </PERSON> said the prison's security force had been doubled and reinforced with special police.
