<HEAD>Woman Decks Tree With Wishbones Painted Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No bones about it, <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>'s Christmas tree, covered from tip to trunk with 525 gold-painted wishbones, is one of a kind `` It's different,'' said <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>, a retired occupational therapist. `` People seem to enjoy it. They've never heard of a wishbone tree.'' <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>'s wishbones are no paltry poultry collection, either. Although it includes the usual chicken and <LOCATION> turkey </LOCATION> bones, it also has fragile pheasant, quail and pigeon wishbones, tiny as thimbles. One comes from a golden eagle, she said. Some date back decades, including the wishbone from the eagle, which was handed down from a friend's grandfather. The golden eagles are now protected from hunters. The collection started when <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>'s father established a poultry farm in the 1930s. Her mother kept chicken, <LOCATION> turkey </LOCATION>, geese and duck wishbones from family dinners on a shelf in the family kitchen. The collection took off from there, said <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>. After a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> newspaper reported on the tree some 30 years ago, <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON> was showered with wishbones from well-wishers. The tree is topped by a big turkey wishbone turned upside down with a bell suspended from the prongs. <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON> says the turkey wishbone from this year's Christmas dinner will hang to one side of the golden eagle wishbone, making a wish for a happy new year.
