ust one tank, which held 250,000 gallons, was affected, and the spill was estimated at 70,000 gallons, officials said. An emergency patch could not be placed on the barge until early Saturday because of rough seas. Oil seeped into <LOCATION> Grays </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> and up the northern part of the inlet as the leaking barge was towed south Friday night to the mouth of the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> said that within <LOCATION> Grays </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, there were traces of oil at the <ORGANIZATION> Oyhut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> and heavier concentrations on Sand and Goose islands. The islands are used as resting spots by harbor seals, but there was no immediate evidence any seals were harmed. Meanwhile, the barge arrived at <LOCATION> Astoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, just inside the mouth of the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, about midday Saturday, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, Ore. The level of oil and seawater in the damaged compartment was lowered by pumping to other compartments on the barge, and the temporary patch in the gashed tank was strengthened, <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> said. Eventually, <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> said, the barge would be towed to <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> where it would be drained and a permanent patch installed. The barge is owned by <PERSON> Sause </PERSON> <PERSON> Bros </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Towing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Coos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, which hired a company to begin cleanup operations, said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauer </PERSON>, manager of bulk products for <PERSON> Sause </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Sause </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> has operated coastal barges for more than 40 years, said <PERSON> Lauer </PERSON>. He declined to comment on whether the spill was the worst in the company's history.
